# Effortless — Attention Mirror for macOS

Effortless transforms your computer into a temple for your attention.
It is a shim into the OS. When it's on, you interact with your computer *through* it.
It does not block. It does not gatekeep. It mirrors your cognitive flow back to you,
making your attention salient so you can tend it like something sacred.

Spiritual successor to the Effortless Chrome extension — elevated from browser to OS,
from static timers to an intelligent mirror powered by local LLM.

## Origin

The original Effortless was a Chrome extension that asked you to declare your purpose
before browsing and assigned a timebox. It worked — users loved it — but it only saw
the browser. The computer is the temple now. The whole screen. Every app. Every switch.

## The Chalice

Your attention is the precious liquid overflowing from a chalice.
You want it given to something sacred, not wasted and tarnished.
The chalice is not a guard. It is a mirror — a still pool of water
showing you your own mind.

The aesthetic treats your attention and intention as something intimate,
precious, to be cared for jealously and only given worthily.

---

Effortless {
  State {
    session: Session | null
    flowState: idle | altar | active | escapeHatch | reflecting
    interruptionStack: [EphemeralContext]  // depth 0 = main flow
    contextStream: stream of { app, windowTitle, timestamp }
  }

  ## The Altar

  The threshold. A full-screen overlay that covers macOS entirely.
  You cannot use your computer without passing through it.
  Not a wall — a doorway. You declare what you will give your attention to.

  AltarView {
    question = "What will you give your attention to?"
    intentionInput: freeform text, centered, warm serif
    timeboxPicker: 15 | 30 | 45 | 60 | 90 | custom minutes
    beginButton: dismisses altar, starts session

    Constraints {
      Cannot be dismissed without setting an intention.
      Cannot be closed via Cmd+W, Escape, or clicking away.
      Covers all screens. Appears above all windows, including fullscreen apps.
      White/cream background. Generous whitespace. Everything breathes.
      The chalice icon presides, quiet and centered.
    }

    (app launches && no active session) => show altar
    (session expires) => show altar
    (wake from sleep) => show altar  // v0.4
  }

  ## The Chalice

  The quiet watcher. Always present during a session.
  Two manifestations: menubar presence and floating overlay.

  MenuBar {
    icon: chalice (simple line art)
    title: remaining time during active session
    dropdown: current intention, time remaining, Complete, Interrupt, Quit
  }

  FloatingOverlay {
    Small, draggable, always-on-top window.
    Shows current intention + countdown timer.
    Warm white, rounded, subtle shadow.
    Unobtrusive but never hidden.

    Constraints {
      Visible on all Spaces and over fullscreen apps.
      Does not steal focus. Does not block interaction.
      Movable by dragging anywhere on it.
    }
  }

  ## Interruptions (Escape Hatch)

  An interruption is giving in to a distraction — abandoning the current
  intention before reaching its outcome to do something else. It may be
  legitimate ("boss called, must respond") or impulsive ("let me check
  Amazon real quick"). Either way, the system makes the cognitive cost
  visible without blocking it.

  Key distinctions:
  - **Interruption**: you *decide* to change intention before completing it.
    "I'm going to stop doing X and do Y instead."
  - **Distraction**: a *prompt* to interrupt (internal thought, external stimulus)
    that you must spend cognitive effort to ignore. Distractions become
    interruptions only when you give in.
  - **Context switch**: navigating between pre-declared contexts. A different
    kind of transition — stays as-is, not treated as an interruption.

  The goal: reduce both interruptions and distractions. A clean cognitive
  graph looks like flow state — one thing at a time, right cognitive load.

  InterruptionFlow {
    trigger: existing interrupt hotkey / menu action
    effect: opens ephemeral "escape hatch" context

    EphemeralContext {
      A single todo — the interruption intention.
      User declares what they're interrupting *for* + sets a timebox.
      Same prompt as regular intention, but visually distinct:
      escape-hatch mode — different background/style to make it feel
      like a detour, not a destination.
      The context *is* the todo — no context label needed.

      The original todo's timer pauses while in the interruption.
    }

    Completing an interruption {
      One action returns you to the previous context/todo.
      Semantically it covers both:
        - "I finished the detour, going back" (completed)
        - "I caught myself, discarding and going back" (discarded)
      The system pops you back one level in the interruption stack.
    }

    Nesting {
      Interruptions can nest (stack). If you interrupt an interruption,
      a guardrail prompt asks: "You're already in an interruption.
      Really interrupt again?" If confirmed, a new level is pushed
      onto the stack. Completing any level pops back to the previous.
      Future: experiment with blocking nesting entirely.
    }

    Constraints {
      You cannot context-switch while in an interruption — you must
      complete/discard it first and return to the main flow.
      The escape-hatch visual treatment is always present so you
      feel the cognitive weight of the detour.
    }
  }

  ## The Cognitive Graph (Mirror View)

  A timeline visualization of every cognitive transition during the day.
  Each node is an intention (todo). Each edge is a transition: completion,
  interruption, or context switch.

  CognitiveGraph {
    nodes: intentions (todos) — what you gave attention to
    edges: transitions between intentions, typed:
      - completion (clean — finished the intention)
      - interruption (friction — abandoned for something unplanned)
      - context switch (neutral — moved between declared contexts)

    The graph is always linear — only one thing active at a time,
    only one transition possible at a time.

    Visualized as a full-day timeline. At a glance you see:
    - How many clean completions vs. interruptions
    - Where the interruption clusters are
    - How deep the nesting went
    - The overall shape of your cognitive flow

    A clean graph = flow state. Jagged with interruptions = fragmented.
    The graph is the mirror — it shows you your day without judgment.
  }

  TransitionEvent {
    timestamp: Date
    from: { contextId, todoId, todoText }
    to: { contextId, todoId, todoText } | EphemeralInterruption
    type: completion | interruption | contextSwitch
    interruptionDepth: Int  // 0 = main flow, 1+ = nested interruption
  }

  ## The Nudge System (Attention Guardian)

  Watches the user's active app and window title. When behavior drifts from
  the declared intention, nudges the user back — gently first, then sharply.
  Uses a local LLM to judge whether the current context is on-task or off-task.

  Detection {
    source: NSWorkspace.didActivateApplicationNotification (app switches)
            + AXUIElement observer (browser tab / window title changes)
    event-driven, not polling — fires instantly on every switch.

    On each event:
      1. Capture { appName, windowTitle, timestamp }
      2. Send to local LLM with current intention + "not distracted" feedback
      3. LLM returns: distracted (yes/no)
      4. If distracted → enter nudge escalation
  }

  LLM Integration {
    provider: Ollama (localhost:11434/api/generate)
    model: user-configurable (default: small/fast model)
    prompt includes:
      - Current intention text
      - Current context label
      - Active app name + window title
      - "Not distracted" history for this context (user feedback)

    Example prompt:
      "User's intention: 'Write PR review'
       Context: 'Work'
       Not distracting for this context: ['Terminal', 'Stack Overflow']
       Currently active: 'YouTube - lofi beats'
       Is the user distracted from their intention? Answer yes or no."

    "Not distracted" feedback {
      When user dismisses a nudge with "not distracted", the app/title
      is added to a per-context allowlist. This persists to disk so the
      LLM learns what's relevant per context across sessions.
      Storage: ~/Library/Application Support/Effortless/context-allowlists.json
    }

    Constraints {
      Runs entirely on-device. No network calls. No cloud.
      Only observes app names and window titles. Never screen content.
      Ollama must be running — if unreachable, nudge system is dormant.
      Model name configurable in Settings.
    }
  }

  NudgeEscalation {
    The escalation is a pressure funnel: gentle → warning → sharp decision.

    Level 0 — Gentle Nudge {
      Trigger: LLM says distracted.
      UI: Small text appears near chalice. Shows app name + intention.
          "You're on [app]. Back to [intention]?"
      Dismissable: "Not distracted" button → feeds back to LLM allowlist.
      If user returns to on-task app → nudge disappears, done.
      If user stays off-task → escalate after configurable delay (default 30s).
    }

    Level 1 — Flash Warning {
      Trigger: gentle nudge timeout expired, still off-task.
      UI: Screen flashes + alert sound. 5-second countdown.
          "Returning you to your intention in 5..."
      Flash and sound are independently toggleable in Settings.
      After 5 seconds → sharp prompt.
    }

    Level 2 — Sharp Prompt {
      Trigger: flash warning countdown finished.
      UI: Fullscreen overlay (like altar). Two choices:
          "Stop" — return to intention (dismisses, 15s grace period)
          "Log Interruption" — opens escape hatch flow
      If user picks "Stop" but LLM detects still distracted after
      grace period (default 15s) → sharp prompt again immediately.
      This creates a loop: you either genuinely return or own the
      interruption. No middle ground.
    }

    Reset: escalation resets when user returns to on-task behavior
    (LLM confirms not distracted) or logs an interruption.
  }

  NudgeSettings {
    enabled: Bool (default: false — opt-in)
    ollamaModel: String (user picks which model)
    gentleNudgeDelay: Int seconds (default: 30)
    gracePeriodAfterStop: Int seconds (default: 15)
    flashEnabled: Bool (default: true)
    soundEnabled: Bool (default: true)
    soundChoice: system alert | custom (future)
  }

  ## The Flow Log

  A record of each session. The raw material for self-knowledge.

  Session {
    id: UUID
    intention: String
    timeboxMinutes: Int
    startedAt: Date
    endedAt: Date | null
    outcome: completed | interrupted | expired
    contextTimeline: [{ app, windowTitle, timestamp }]  // v0.2
    transitions: [TransitionEvent]  // cognitive graph edges
    reflection: String | null  // v0.3
  }

  SessionLog {
    storage: ~/Library/Application Support/Effortless/sessions.json
    Constraints {
      100% local. User-owned. No telemetry.
      JSON format, human-readable.
    }
    fn log(session);
    fn loadAll;
    fn recentSessions;
  }

  ## Session Flow

  ```mermaid
  stateDiagram-v2
      [*] --> Altar
      Altar --> Active: intention + timebox set
      Active --> Reflecting: user completes todo
      Active --> EscapeHatch: user interrupts
      Active --> Altar: timer expires
      Active --> GentleNudge: LLM detects distraction
      GentleNudge --> Active: user returns / "not distracted"
      GentleNudge --> FlashWarning: still off-task after delay
      FlashWarning --> SharpPrompt: 5s countdown expires
      SharpPrompt --> Active: user picks "Stop"
      SharpPrompt --> EscapeHatch: user picks "Log Interruption"
      SharpPrompt --> SharpPrompt: "Stop" but still distracted after grace
      EscapeHatch --> Active: interruption completed/discarded
      EscapeHatch --> EscapeHatch: nested interruption (with guardrail)
      Reflecting --> Altar: reflection acknowledged
  ```

  fn begin(intention, minutes);
  fn complete;
  fn interrupt;  // opens escape hatch, pushes onto interruption stack
  fn completeInterruption;  // pops stack, returns to previous context
  fn expire;

  match (flowState) {
    case idle => show altar
    case altar => await intention
    case active => run timer, show chalice, monitor context
    case escapeHatch => pause original timer, run interruption timer,
                        show escape-hatch visual treatment
    case reflecting => show reflection prompt, then return to altar
  }

  ## Design Language — Sacred Minimalism

  Aesthetic {
    backgrounds: white, cream — clean, spacious, like a quiet room
    typography: warm serif — intimate, not corporate
    icon: chalice — simple line art, central
    accents: subtle gold/amber — warmth without flash
    whitespace: generous — every element breathes
    animations: slow, deliberate — like pouring water

    Constraints {
      No gamification. No streaks. No scores. No achievements.
      This is a mirror, not a game.
      No "productivity bro" energy. Monastic. Reverent. Intimate.
    }
  }

  ToneOfVoice {
    Intimate, second-person.
    "What will you give your attention to?"
    Never commanding or guilt-inducing.
    Reflective questions, not directives.
    "You've been here for 12 minutes. Is this where you want to be?"
  }

  ## Architecture

  Tech {
    language: Swift / SwiftUI
    windowControl: AppKit (NSWindow) for overlay levels and menubar
    monitoring: NSWorkspace notifications + CGWindowListCopyWindowInfo + AXUIElement
    llm: Ollama / MLX — local, on-device (v0.3)
    storage: JSON files, local disk
    platform: macOS 14+
  }

  Privacy {
    Constraints {
      100% local. No network calls. No telemetry. No cloud.
      Screen content is never captured or stored.
      Only app names and window titles are observed.
      Session logs stored locally, user-owned.
    }
  }

  ## Roadmap

  v0.1 — The Altar {
    Menubar app with chalice icon.
    Full-screen altar overlay: intention + timebox + begin.
    Floating chalice overlay: intention + countdown.
    Session flow: begin, complete, interrupt, expire.
    Basic session logging to JSON.
  }

  v0.2 — The Mirror (Context Awareness) {
    Active window monitoring (app name + window title).
    Context timeline logged per session.
    Session review: see where your attention went.
    Rule-based drift detection.
  }

  v0.3 — The Witness (Nudge System) {
    Active app + window title monitoring via accessibility APIs.
    Local LLM integration via Ollama for distraction detection.
    Nudge escalation: gentle text → flash warning → sharp stop/interrupt prompt.
    Per-context "not distracted" feedback loop into LLM prompt.
    Configurable: model, timing, flash, sound.
  }

  v0.4 — The Temple (Deep Integration) {
    Launch on login. Altar on wake.
    Multi-session patterns across days/weeks.
    Global keyboard shortcuts.
    Do Not Disturb integration.
    Flow log export.
  }
}
